1. Sensu backend/agent image


2. Sensu runtime assets



Your uploaded transcript also says the main migration work is validating the Sensu image and runtime assets, especially Ruby-based assets. 


---

1. Sensu image work

Goal

Replace the current AMD64-only Sensu image with an image that supports:

linux/arm64

Command to verify the image

export SENSU_IMAGE="sensu/sensu:<version>"

docker buildx imagetools inspect "$SENSU_IMAGE" | grep -E "linux/(amd64|arm64)"

Expected output must include:

linux/amd64
linux/arm64

If linux/arm64 is missing, do not use that image.


---

Update image in Kustomize

Go to your Sensu repo:

cd <sensu-git-repo>
git checkout STG
git pull

Find current image:

grep -R "image:" sensu-go/

Update image using Kustomize:

cd <kustomize-overlay-folder>

kustomize edit set image <old-sensu-image>=sensu/sensu:<version>

Example:

kustomize edit set image <private-sensu-image>:latest=sensu/sensu:6.14.0

Verify rendered manifest:

kustomize build . | grep -A2 -B2 "image:"


---

2. Sensu asset work

Goal

Every Sensu asset used by checks/handlers must have an ARM64 build.

Each asset should have:

url: <arm64-tarball-url>
sha512: <arm64-sha512>
filters:
  - entity.system.os == 'linux'
  - entity.system.arch == 'arm64'


---

Go to asset folder

cd <sensu-git-repo>/sensu-go/base/asset


---

Find assets missing ARM64

grep -L "entity.system.arch == 'arm64'" *.yml *.yaml

Every file shown by this command needs to be fixed.


---

Find unsafe assets

grep -R "filters: null" .

Any result is risky.

Fix it. Do not leave AMD64 assets with:

filters: null

For AMD64 builds, use:

filters:
  - entity.system.os == 'linux'
  - entity.system.arch == 'amd64'

For ARM64 builds, use:

filters:
  - entity.system.os == 'linux'
  - entity.system.arch == 'arm64'


---

Find AMD64-only references

grep -R "linux_amd64\|amd64" .

For each AMD64 asset, add a matching ARM64 build if available.


---

3. Asset YAML format to use

Each asset should look like this:

type: Asset
api_version: core/v2
metadata:
  name: <asset-name>
spec:
  builds:
    - url: <asset-linux-amd64.tar.gz>
      sha512: <amd64-sha512>
      filters:
        - entity.system.os == 'linux'
        - entity.system.arch == 'amd64'

    - url: <asset-linux-arm64.tar.gz>
      sha512: <arm64-sha512>
      filters:
        - entity.system.os == 'linux'
        - entity.system.arch == 'arm64'

Keep the same:

metadata:
  name: <existing-asset-name>

Do not rename assets unless absolutely required.


---

4. Get SHA512 for ARM64 asset tarball

For each ARM64 asset URL:

export ASSET_URL="<arm64-asset-tarball-url>"

curl -L -o /tmp/asset_arm64.tar.gz "$ASSET_URL"

sha512sum /tmp/asset_arm64.tar.gz

Copy the SHA512 value into the asset YAML.


---

5. Required assets to check

Based on your setup, check these files carefully:

ls -1 | grep -E "http|aggregate|sns|cloudwatch|aws|ruby|plugins"

You need ARM64 support for:

http-check
aggregate-check
aws-sns-handler
cloudwatch-check
plugins-aws
plugins-http
ruby-runtime

Most important one:

sensu-ruby-runtime

If sensu-ruby-runtime is still AMD64-only, Ruby-based checks may fail on ARM64 with:

exec format error
ruby not found
no matching asset build


